results.name: Number of ways to write n as sum of cubes>1.
comment: Conjecture (lower bound): for all k exists b(k) such that a(n)>k for n>b(k); see b(0)=A078129(83)=154 and b(1)=A078130(63)=218.
link: Vaclav Kotesovec, Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000
Index entries for sequences related to sums of cubes
Eric Weisstein's World of Mathematics, Cubic Number.
formula: a(n) = 1/n*Sum_{k=1..n} (b(k)-1)*a(n-k), a(0) = 1, where b(k) is sum of cube divisors of k. - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Nov 20 2002
